ce:section.ce:para:
Surface electrostatic interaction allows for the Porp-CQDs to easily conjugate with metal ions since it is negatively charged in a neutral medium. For bore well water analysis, the fluorescence signal help for the enhancement of the emission peak at 500 nm for Porp-CQDs. The quenching phenomenon is observed at 670 nm under the 430 nm excitation. The process is significantly influence the energy transfer between the metal ions and the Porp-CQDs. The as-synthesized Porp-CQDs has a distinct emission peak at 670 nm, with additional peak enhancement observed at low intensity for the addition of various bore well water samples. The sample of bore-well water is collected from the campus (Latitude11.10222° & Longitude 76.96571°) ranging from 0 μM to 250 μM (in Fig. 8A to C). The excited state of electrons present in the surface trap states of CQDs may be transmitted to the half-filled 3d orbitals of Zn2+, enabling metal ion sensing [56]. The controlled performance of the pure porphyrin is carried out with TPPS4 samples in bore well water and in the presence of different metal salts of Zn2+, Cu2+, Ni2+, and Mn2+ (0.01 M concentration). The TPPS4 samples (250 μM) show an emission at 643 nm and 700 nm which are responsible for the Q-bands with an excitation wavelength of 430 nm in bore well water. No spectral changes are observed between 0 μM to 250 μM of TPPS4 addition in Fig. 8A. The as-synthesized Prop-CQDs in addition to 0 μM to 250 μM of bore well water gradually quench the major peak (670 nm) and simultaneously improve the detection of the Zn2+ metal ion at 500 nm (Fig. 8B&C). Fig. 8D describes the absorption spectra of Porp-CQDs and the energy transfer diagram of Porp-CQDs complex formation with Zn2+ ion. The mechanism suggested for the above observed spectral changes may be summarized as follows. Porp-CQDs is a fluorophore that absorbs light energy in the ground state (S

                           0
                        ) and then excites the electrons to the higher energy excited state (S

                           1
                        ). Eventually, a quick, non-radiative energy transfer to the state with the lowest vibration occurs, followed by a shift to the ground state [57]. During the fluorescence spectroscopic investigation, the Porp-CQDs are excited at the optimal wavelength of 430 nm and emitted fluorescence at a maximum of 670 nm. As stated by Yadolah et al. (2022), citrazinic acid with a single aromatic ring emits blue colors. The excited state of electrons present in CQDs is transmitted to the half-filled 3d orbitals of Zn2+, enabling metal ion sensing [29].
